{{distinguish|Cat Fanciers' Association}}
{{Infobox organization |name = American Cat Fanciers Association |image = |image_border = |size = 200px |alt = |caption = |map = |msize = |malt = |mcaption = |abbreviation = |motto = |formation = {{start date and age|1955}} |extinction = |type = |status = |purpose = |headquarters = |location = |region_served = United States |membership = |language = English |leader_title = |leader_name = |main_organ = |parent_organization = |affiliations = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = |remarks = }}
The '''American Cat Fanciers Association''' ('''ACFA''') is an [[United States|American]] [[non-profit organization]] formed with the intent of allowing greater flexibility in the development of [[pedigreed]] cats. The ACFA is a cat registry for purebred, pedigreed cats, experimental breeds of cats, and household pet cats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyberpedia.com/cats.htm|title=Encyberpedia}}</ref>
ACFA sanctioned cat shows include classes for championship adult cats, championship altered cats, registered kittens from the age of four to eight months, and household pet cats. Wins from licensed shows can be used to claim titles including championships and multiple championships, grand championships and multiple grand championships, and the household pet titles of Royal Household Pet and Supreme Household Pet.
ACFA is directly affiliated with the [[Cat Aficionado Association]] of China, who use the ACFA breed standards.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
==Founding== ACFA was founded in 1955 by a group of cat fanciers desiring to show their cats in a democratic association, that is, one where individual members had voting rights on election of officers, acceptance of new show rules, by-laws and breed standards and acceptance of new breeds of cats.
