{{Africa topic|Ethnic groups in}}

[[Category:Ethnic groups in Algeria|*]]

The ethnic composition of [[Ivory Coast]] is complex with more than 60 ethnic groups represented.

The [[Akan people|Akan]] group, which primarily occupies the eastern and central regions of the country, accounts for about 42.1 percent of the population.{{cn|date=April 2017}} The [[Baoulé people|Baoulé]] are the single largest subgroup of the Akan people, accounting for about 20 percent of the total population. The [[Gur languages|Voltaiques]] (Gur) account for about 17.6% of the population. The Northern [[Mandé peoples|Mandes]] from the northwest region of the country make up about 16.5% of the population. The [[Kru people|Krou]] people in the southwest account for about 11 percent; the [[Bété people|Bété]] are the largest subgroup.{{cn|date=April 2017}} The Southern Mandes from the western regions account for about 10% of the population. Non-Africans include about 14,000 [[French people|French]] and 130,000 [[Lebanese people in Côte d'Ivoire|Lebanese]] expatriates.

