The exact number of '''Surinamese people in Belgium''' is unknown. The (legal) Surinamese community in the Belgian capital is in any case very small: In 2015, only two Surinamese women were enrolled in Brussels<ref>[[Brussel (stad)|Brussel-Stad]], [[Laken (België)|Laken]], [[Neder-Over-Heembeek]] en [[Haren (Brussel)|Haren]]</ref> along with a number of men); in 2012 this was only one. According to figures quoted "in the corridors" of the Surinamese Embassy in Belgium, the total number of Surinamese people in Belgium would be about 30,000, or at least 20,000.<ref name="radio10">[[Radio 10 (Suriname)|Radio 10]], "''[http://www.radio10.sr/nieuws/precieze-cijfers-illegale-surinamers-in-belgie-nu-in-kaart-gebracht/60848 Precieze cijfers illegale Surinamers in België nu in kaart gebracht]''" (27 oktober 2016)</ref> According to the diaspora organisation Suriname Diaspora Solidarity Belgium (Surisobe), half of them are illegally present in the country. However, it is not known how Surisobe calculated this number. In October 2016, the embassy indicated that more precise figures are now being mapped out.<ref name="radio102">[[Radio 10 (Suriname)|Radio 10]], "''[http://www.radio10.sr/nieuws/precieze-cijfers-illegale-surinamers-in-belgie-nu-in-kaart-gebracht/60848 Precieze cijfers illegale Surinamers in België nu in kaart gebracht]''" (27 oktober 2016)</ref>

Some of the Surinamese people in Belgium use the so-called "Belgian route": they come and live in Belgium with their Dutch partner to circumvent the stricter rules on family reunification in the Netherlands. Their stay in the country is therefore only temporary.<ref>[[Het Nieuwsblad]], "''[http://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20141022_01335730 Even in België wonen levert Nederlandse papieren op]''" (22 oktober 2014)</ref>

There have been repeated incidents involving Surinamese people in Belgium in drug trafficking to the country. From 1990-1991, a group of Surinamese people with ties to the [[Surinamese army]] smuggled [[cocaine]] using their own airline, [[Trans-Caribbean Airlines]], to transport the drugs from Paramaribo to Ostend airport.<ref>[[NRC Handelsblad]], "''[https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/1992/03/06/oostende-station-voor-cocaine-uit-suriname-surinaams-7135508-a381100 Oostende station voor cocaïne uit Suriname; Surinaams leger opnieuw betrokken bij smokkel van drugs]''" (6 maart 1992)</ref>. In 2013, four people, including two Surinamese people, suspected of taking small quantities of cannabis and cocaine from the Netherlands to Belgium every fortnight, were arrested<ref>[[Suriname Herald]], "''[http://www.srherald.com/suriname/2013/08/25/twee-surinamers-verdacht-van-drugshandel-in-belgie/ Twee Surinamers verdacht van drugshandel in België]{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}''" (25 augustus 2013)</ref>.

In 2015 an organisation of fifteen Surinamese people smuggled [[cocaine]] into Belgium and sold [[MDMA|ecstasy]] and [[cannabis]] in [[Antwerp]]. In 2016, ten people were arrested near Mol and Balen who were suspected of smuggling large quantities of cocaine from Suriname to Belgium via [[French Guiana]]. In addition, two were picked up in [[Cayenne]].<ref>[[De Morgen]], "''[http://www.demorgen.be/binnenland/surinaamse-drugsbende-opgerold-in-mol-en-omgeving-baebef78/ Surinaamse drugsbende opgerold in Mol en omgeving]''" (11 oktober 2016)</ref> The group consisted of both Surinamese and [[Surinamese people in the Netherlands|Dutch people of Surinamese descent]].<ref name="radio10drugs">Radio 10, "''[http://www.radio10.sr/nieuws/in-belgische-drugsaffaire-onderschepte-cocaine-uit-suriname-afkomstig/60301 In Belgische Drugsaffaire: Onderschepte cocaïne uit Suriname afkomstig]''" (14 oktober 2016)</ref>

Also, this is a small French Guianese community in the Walloon community, also a tiny Guyanese community in the Flemish community.

